{{Voting}}
In [[representative democracy]], the '''popular vote''' is the total number or [[percentage]] of [[vote]]s received by a [[Political party|party]], candidate or group of candidates, as opposed to the number of seats they win in the [[representative assembly]] or, as in the [[United States]], in the [[Electoral College (United States)|Electoral College]] in a [[United States presidential election|presidential election]]. There have been five presidential elections in which the person who [[United States presidential elections in which the winner lost the popular vote|became president received fewer popular votes than their opponent]], the most recent being the [[United States presidential election, 2016|2016 presidential election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.snopes.com/2016/11/13/who-won-the-popular-vote/|title=Who Won the Popular Vote?|last=Evon|first=Dan|website=snopes|access-date=2016-11-14}}</ref>

