{{Infobox U.S. legislation | name = Research Works Act | fullname = "To ensure the continued publication and integrity of peer-reviewed research works by the private sector." —H.R. 3699<ref name="rosen"/> | acronym = | nickname = | sections amended = | leghisturl = | introducedin = House | introducedbill = {{USBill|112|H.R.|3699}} | introducedby = [[Darrell Issa]] (R-CA) | introduceddate = December 16, 2011 | committees = [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]] }}
The '''Research Works Act''', 102 H.R. 3699, was a [[bill (proposed law)|bill]] that was introduced in the [[United States House of Representatives]] at the [[112th United States Congress]] on December 16, 2011, by Representative [[Darrell Issa]] (R-CA) and co-sponsored by [[Carolyn B. Maloney]] (D-NY).<ref>{{USBill|112|H.R.|3699}}</ref> The bill contained provisions to prohibit [[open-access mandate]]s for federally funded research<ref name=sparc>{{cite web|last=Joseph|first=Heather|title=Take Action: Oppose H.R. 3699, a new bill to block public access to publicly funded research|url=http://www.arl.org/sparc/media/blog/12-0106.shtml|work=SPARC blog|accessdate=January 8, 2012|date=January 6, 2012}}</ref> and effectively revert<ref name="ALA">[http://www.districtdispatch.org/2012/01/trying-to-roll-back-the-clock-on-open-access-research-works-act-introduced/ Trying to roll back the clock on Open Access] statement by the [[American Library Association]] that "vehemently oppose[e]d'' the bill".</ref> the United States' [[NIH Public Access Policy|National Institutes of Health Public Access Policy]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://publicaccess.nih.gov/policy.htm |title=NIH Public Access Policy Details |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62vO48RCv?url=http://publicaccess.nih.gov/policy.htm |archivedate=2011-11-03 |publisher=nih.gov |accessdate=2012-05-27 |deadurl=yes }}</ref> which requires taxpayer-funded research to be freely accessible online.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dobbs |first=David |title=Congress Considers Paywalling Science You Already Paid For |url=https://www.wired.com/wiredscience/2012/01/congress-considers-paywalling-science-you-already-paid-for/ |newspaper=Wired |date=January 6, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64cQ2CPft?url=http://www.wired.com/wiredscience/2012/01/congress-considers-paywalling-science-you-already-paid-for/ |archivedate=January 11, 2012 |deadurl=no }}</ref> If enacted, it would have also severely restricted the sharing of [[scientific data]].<ref>Piwowar, Heather. [http://researchremix.wordpress.com/2012/01/07/rwa-data/ Research Works Act Attacks Data Dissemination Too]</ref> The bill was referred to the [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]],<ref>[http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h112-3699&tab=committees H.R. 3699: Research Works Act: Committee Assignments]</ref> of which Issa is the chair.<ref>[http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c112:H.RES.6: List of members elected to the standing committees of the House of Representatives on January 5, 2011]</ref> Similar bills were introduced in 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/~peters/fos/newsletter/10-02-08.htm#nih |title=A bill to overturn the NIH policy |author=Peter Suber |date=October 2, 2008 |work=SPARC Open Access Newsletter |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64iKf5dBA?url=http://www.earlham.edu/~peters/fos/newsletter/10-02-08.htm |archivedate=January 15, 2012 |accessdate=January 15, 2012 |deadurl=yes }}</ref> and 2009<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/~peters/fos/newsletter/03-02-09.htm#conyers |title=Re-introduction of the bill to kill the NIH policy |author=Peter Suber |date=March 2, 2009 |work=SPARC Open Access Newsletter |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64iKodJiR?url=http://www.earlham.edu/~peters/fos/newsletter/03-02-09.htm |archivedate=January 15, 2012 |accessdate=January 15, 2012 |deadurl=yes }}</ref> but have not been enacted since.<ref name="rosen">{{cite web|last=Rosen |first=Rebecca J. |title=Why Is Open-Internet Champion Darrell Issa Supporting an Attack on Open Science? |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2012/01/why-is-open-internet-champion-darrell-issa-supporting-an-attack-on-open-science/250929/ |publisher=The Atlantic |date=January 5, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64cPt2WJO?url=http://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2012/01/why-is-open-internet-champion-darrell-issa-supporting-an-attack-on-open-science/250929/ |archivedate=January 11, 2012 |deadurl=no }}</ref>
On February 27, 2012 [[Elsevier]], a major publisher, announced that it was withdrawing support for the Act.<ref>[http://www.elsevier.com/about/company-information/policies/message-on-the-research-works-act Elsevier withdraws support for the Research Works Act]</ref> Later that day, Issa and Maloney issued a statement saying that they would not push for legislative action on the bill.<ref>{{cite news|last=Howard|first=Jennifer|title=Legislation to Bar Public-Access Requirement on Federal Research Is Dead|url=http://chronicle.com/article/Legislation-to-Bar/130949/|accessdate=February 27, 2012|date=February 27, 2012}}</ref>
==Reception== The bill was supported by the [[Association of American Publishers]] (AAP)<ref>{{cite web|last=Sporkin |first=Andi |title=Publishers Applaud "Research Works Act," Bipartisan Legislation To End Government Mandates on Private-Sector Scholarly Publishing |url=http://www.publishers.org/press/56/ |publisher=Association of American Publishers |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64VQfm6rv?url=http://www.publishers.org/press/56/ |archivedate=January 7, 2012 |date=December 23, 2011 |deadurl=no }}</ref> and the [[Copyright Alliance]].<ref>[http://copyrightalliance.org/news.php?id=130 Statement from Copyright Alliance Executive Director Sandra Aistars, Re: Introduction of H.R. 3699, the Research Works Act]</ref>
The [[Scholarly Publishing and Academic Resources Coalition]],<ref name=sparc/> the [[Alliance for Taxpayer Access]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Call to action: Oppose H.R. 3699, a bill to block public access to publicly funded research|url=http://www.taxpayeraccess.org/action/action_access/12-0106.shtml|work=Alliance for Taxpayer Access|accessdate=January 8, 2012|first=Heather |last=Joseph|first2=Jennifer |last2=McLennan|date=January 6, 2012}}</ref> the [[American Library Association]],<ref name="ALA"/> the [[International Society for Computational Biology]],<ref>{{cite web|title=ISCB to respond to Research Works Act (HR 3699) |url=http://sciblogs.co.nz/code-for-life/2012/01/11/iscb-to-respond-to-research-works-act-hr-3699/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64iKGtgow?url=http://sciblogs.co.nz/code-for-life/2012/01/11/iscb-to-respond-to-research-works-act-hr-3699/ |archivedate=January 15, 2012 |work=Code for Life |accessdate=January 15, 2012 |first=Grant |last=Jacobs |date=January 11, 2012 |deadurl=yes }}</ref> the [[Confederation of Open Access Repositories]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Maximizing the visibility of research outputs: COAR call for action |url=http://www.coar-repositories.org/news/coar-writes-open-letter-as-reaction-to-elseviers-practices/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/65Fr6nhEy?url=http://www.coar-repositories.org/news/coar-writes-open-letter-as-reaction-to-elseviers-practices/ |archivedate=February 6, 2012 |work=Confederation of Open Access Repositories website |accessdate=February 6, 2012 |first=Maxie |last=Putlitz |date=February 6, 2012 |deadurl=yes }}</ref> and prominent [[open science]] and [[open access]] advocates criticized the Research Works Act,<ref>{{cite web|title=Research Works Act H.R.3699: The Private Publishing Tail Trying To Wag The Public Research Dog, Yet Again|url=http://openaccess.eprints.org/index.php?/archives/867-guid.html|work=Open Access Archivangelism|accessdate=January 8, 2012|first=Stevan |last=Harnad|authorlink=Stevan Harnad|date=January 7, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Elsevier-funded NY Congresswoman Carolyn Maloney Wants to Deny Americans Access to Taxpayer Funded Research |url=http://www.michaeleisen.org/blog/?p=807 |accessdate=January 8, 2012 |first=Michael |last=Eisen |authorlink=Michael Eisen |date=January 5, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64cQIZT70?url=http://www.michaeleisen.org/blog/?p=807 |archivedate=January 11, 2012 |deadurl=no }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Scholarly Poor could lose access to scientific research; this is serious|url=http://blogs.ch.cam.ac.uk/pmr/2012/01/06/the-scholarly-poor-could-lose-access-to-scientific-research-this-is-serious/|accessdate=January 8, 2012|first=Peter |last=Murray-Rust|authorlink=Peter Murray-Rust|date=January 6, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Oppose H.R. 3699: To ensure the continued publication and integrity of peer-reviewed research works by the private sector|url=https://www.popvox.com/bills/us/112/hr3699/comment/263013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119104636/https://www.popvox.com/bills/us/112/hr3699/comment/263013|archivedate=2012-01-19|work=Letters to Congress|accessdate=January 8, 2012|first=Tim |last=O'Reilly|authorlink=Tim O'Reilly|date=January 5, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://plus.google.com/u/0/109377556796183035206/posts/QYAH1jSJG6L |title=New bill to block open access to {{Sic|hide=y|publicly|-}}funded research |author=Peter Suber |date=January 6, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64iLSNKVs?url=https://plus.google.com/u/0/109377556796183035206/posts/QYAH1jSJG6L |archivedate=January 15, 2012 |accessdate=January 15, 2012 |deadurl=yes }}</ref> some of them urging [[scholarly society|scholarly societies]] to resign from the AAP because of its support for the bill.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our scientific societies need to quit the Association of American Publishers|url=http://www.michaeleisen.org/blog/?p=837|accessdate=January 8, 2012|first=Michael |last=Eisen|authorlink=Michael Eisen|date=January 7, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Dupuis|first=John|title=Scholarly Societies: It's time to abandon the AAP over The Research Works Act|url=http://scienceblogs.com/confessions/2012/01/scholarly_societies_its_time_t.php|work=Confessions of a Science Librarian|date=January 5, 2012}}</ref> Several AAP members, including [[MIT Press]], [[Rockefeller University Press]], [[Nature Publishing Group]], [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] stated their opposition to the bill but signaled no intention to leave the association.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://poynder.blogspot.com/2012/01/mit-press-distances-itself-from.html|title=MIT Press distances itself from Research Works Act |author=Richard Poynder |date=January 11, 2012 |work=Open and Shut|accessdate=January 15, 2012}}</ref> Other AAP members stated their opposition to the bill<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cyber.law.harvard.edu/hoap/Notes_on_the_Research_Works_Act#|title=Notes on the Research Works Act |accessdate=February 7, 2012}}</ref> as did the [[Association of American Universities]] (AAU) and the [[Association of Public and Land-grant Universities]].<ref>{{cite web|title=AAU, APLU Express Opposition to Research Works Act |url=http://www.aau.edu/WorkArea/DownloadAsset.aspx?id=13018 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/65GQT8paC?url=http://www.aau.edu/WorkArea/DownloadAsset.aspx?id=13018 |archivedate=February 7, 2012 |work=Association of American Universities website |accessdate=February 6, 2012 |author=Hunter R. Rawlings III |date=February 6, 2012 |deadurl=yes }}</ref> Several public health groups opposed the bill.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seven public health groups write to oppose the "Research Works Act" |url=http://keionline.org/node/1352 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/65KiOYS6E?url=http://keionline.org/node/1352 |archivedate=February 9, 2012 |work=Knowledge Ecology International |accessdate=February 9, 2012 |author=Hunter R. Rawlings III |date=February 9, 2012 |deadurl=yes }}</ref>
Opponents stressed particularly the effects on public availability of biomedical research results, such as those funded by [[NIH]] grants, submitting that under the bill "taxpayers who already paid for the research would have to pay again to read the results".<ref>{{cite news|title=Research Bought, Then Paid For|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/11/opinion/research-bought-then-paid-for.html|accessdate=January 11, 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=January 10, 2012|first=Michael |last=Eisen|authorlink=Michael Eisen}}</ref> Mike Taylor from the [[University of Bristol]] said that the bill's denial of access to scientific research would cause "preventable deaths in developing countries" and "an incalculable loss to science", and said Representatives Issa and Maloney were motivated by multiple donations they had received from the academic publisher [[Elsevier]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2012/jan/16/academic-publishers-enemies-science|title=Academic publishers have become the enemies of science|date=16 January 2011|first=Mike|last=Taylor|work=The Guardian}}</ref>
An online petition – ''[[The Cost of Knowledge]]'' – inspired by [[UK|British]] mathematician and [[Fields Medal|Fields medalist]] [[Timothy Gowers]] to raise awareness of the bill, to call for lower prices for journals and to promote increased open access to information, was signed by more than 10,000 scholars.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Cost of Knowledge|url=http://thecostofknowledge.com/|accessdate=2 March 2012}}</ref> Signatories vowed to withhold their support from Elsevier journals as editors, [[Peer review|reviewers]] or authors "unless they radically change how they operate". On February 27, 2012, Elsevier announced its withdrawal of support for the bill, citing concerns from journal authors, editors, and reviewers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Elsevier withdraws support for the Research Works Act|url=http://www.elsevier.com/wps/find/intro.cws_home/newmessagerwa|publisher=Elsevier|date=February 27, 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229220817/http://www.elsevier.com/wps/find/intro.cws_home/newmessagerwa|archivedate=February 29, 2012|df=}}</ref> While participants in the boycott celebrated the dropping of support for the Research Works Act,<ref>{{cite web|last=Doctorow|first=Cory|title=Elsevier withdraws support from Research Works Act, bill collapses|url=http://boingboing.net/2012/02/28/elsevier-withdraws-support-fro.html|work=BoingBoing|accessdate=2 March 2012|authorlink=Cory Doctorow|date=28 February 2012}}</ref> Elsevier denied that their action was a result of the boycott and stated that they took this action at the request of those researchers who did not participate in the boycott.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://chronicle.com/article/Legislation-to-Bar/130949/ |title=Legislation to Bar Public-Access Requirement on Federal Research Is Dead |first=Jennifer |last=Howard |work=[[The Chronicle of Higher Education]] |date=27 February 2012 |accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref>
== Related legislation and executive action== The Research Works Act followed other attempts to challenge institutional open-access mandates in the US. On September 9, 2008, an earlier bill aimed at reversing the NIH's Public Access Policy – the [[Fair Copyright in Research Works Act]], or Conyers Bill – was introduced as 110 H. R. 6845 in the House of Representatives at the [[110th United States Congress]] by U.S Representative [[John Conyers]] (D-MI), with three cosponsors.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bill Text 110th Congress (2007–2008) H.R.6845.IH|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d110:HR06845:|publisher=The Library of Congress|accessdate=2015-10-24}}</ref> It was referred to the [[House Committee on the Judiciary]], to which Conyers delivered an introduction on September 10, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Speech of John Conyers in the House of Representatives, September 10, 2008|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/D?r110:2:./temp/~r110kLvpzy:|publisher=The Library of Congress|accessdate=2015-10-24}}</ref> After the start of the [[111th United States Congress]], Conyers and six-cosponsors reintroduced the bill to the House of Representatives as 111 H. R. 801 on February 3, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bill Text 111th Congress (2009–2010) H.R.801.IH|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c111:H.R.801:|publisher=The Library of Congress|accessdate=2015-10-24}}</ref> It was on the same day referred to the House Committee on the Judiciary and on March 16 to the [[Subcommittee on Courts and Competition Policy]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Bill summary and status, H.R.801|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdquery/z?d111:HR00801:@@@X|publisher=The Library of Congress|accessdate=2015-10-24}}</ref>
On the other hand, the [[Federal Research Public Access Act]] proposed to expand the open public access mandate to research funded by eleven U.S. federal agencies. Originally introduced to the Senate in 2006 by [[John Cornyn]] (R-TX) with two cosponsors,<ref>{{USBill|109|S.|2695}}</ref> it was reintroduced in 2009 by Lieberman, co-sponsored by Cornyn,<ref>{{USBill|111|S.|1373}}</ref> and again in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kaiser|first=Jocelyn|title=Lawmakers Reintroduce Public Access Bill|url=http://news.sciencemag.org/scienceinsider/2012/02/lawmakers-reintroduce-public-access.html|work=ScienceInsider|publisher=American Association for the Advancement of Science|accessdate=10 February 2012|date=10 February 2012}}</ref> These bills proposed requiring that those eleven agencies with research expenditures over $100 million create online repositories of journal articles of the research completed by that agency and make them publicly available without charge within six months after it has been published in a peer-reviewed journal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Federal Research Public Access Act 2006|url=http://www.taxpayeraccess.org/issues/frpaa2006/index.shtml}}</ref> On February 22, 2013 the [[Barack Obama|Obama]] administration issued a similar policy memorandum, directing Federal agencies with more than $100 million in annual research and development expenditures to develop plans to make research freely available to the public within one year of publication in most cases.<ref>[http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/digital/copyright/article/56076-in-historic-act-obama-administration-issues-public-access-directive.html White House Issues Public Access Directive<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
